Wiring Schematic
The schematic shows how all the major components are connected in this direct drive wheel build.
Main Components:

STM32F407 Board – The main controller that runs OpenFFBoard firmware and communicates with the PC via USB.
Elecrow TMC4671 FOC Driver – The motor driver that converts the STM32 commands into precise torque control for the stepper motor.
12Nm NEMA 34 Closed-Loop Stepper Motor – The main actuator providing force feedback.
48-60V Power Supply – Powers the motor and driver.
10Ω 50W Brake Resistor – Protects the system from voltage spikes.
80mm Cooling Fan – Keeps the TMC4671 driver cool during use.

Key Connections:

Power: The 48-60V PSU connects to the TMC4671 driver’s VMOT and GND terminals. The brake resistor is wired across the PB+ and PB- terminals.
Motor Phases: The stepper motor’s four phase wires (A+, A-, B+, B-) connect directly to the TMC4671’s Phase A and Phase B outputs.
Encoder: The motor’s 1000 PPR encoder (A+, B+, Z+, 5V, GND) connects to the TMC4671’s ENC header for precise position feedback.
SPI Communication: The STM32F407 talks to the TMC4671 via SPI (SCK, MOSI, MISO, CS) for real-time torque control.
Logic Power: The TMC4671 provides +5V and GND to power the STM32F407 board.
USB: The STM32F407 connects to the PC via USB for configuration and force feedback data.

The STM32F407 board is designed to stack directly on top of the TMC4671 driver for clean, short connections.
